{"data":{"page":{"coverImage":{"title":"Portlandia technology loop","alt":"","fluid":{"base64":"data:image/png;base64,","aspectRatio":2.84625,"src":"//images.ctfassets.net/jbawaa5001ko/61pVB8hZSHeHHaMsyLoups/9e5316bd056549f7caeefee810f43e9a/Screen-Shot-2017-04-23-at-11.31.39-AM.png?w=1920&q=50","srcSet":"//images.ctfassets.net/jbawaa5001ko/61pVB8hZSHeHHaMsyLoups/9e5316bd056549f7caeefee810f43e9a/Screen-Shot-2017-04-23-at-11.31.39-AM.png?w=480&h=169&q=50 480w,\n//images.ctfassets.net/jbawaa5001ko/61pVB8hZSHeHHaMsyLoups/9e5316bd056549f7caeefee810f43e9a/Screen-Shot-2017-04-23-at-11.31.39-AM.png?w=960&h=337&q=50 960w,\n//images.ctfassets.net/jbawaa5001ko/61pVB8hZSHeHHaMsyLoups/9e5316bd056549f7caeefee810f43e9a/Screen-Shot-2017-04-23-at-11.31.39-AM.png?w=1920&h=675&q=50 1920w,\n//images.ctfassets.net/jbawaa5001ko/61pVB8hZSHeHHaMsyLoups/9e5316bd056549f7caeefee810f43e9a/Screen-Shot-2017-04-23-at-11.31.39-AM.png?w=2277&h=800&q=50 2277w","sizes":"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px"}},"content":{"json":{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"It’s 11:45, and you need a good night’s sleep badly, but your brain’s not cooperating. So you think… OK, I’ll just respond to a couple emails, then I’ll be tired enough for bed.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"Five minutes later it’s 2:37am, and you suddenly find yourself watching a video of Paula Deen deep-frying cheesecake.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"Wait… what the hell just happened?","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"You got stuck in a technology loop, that’s what.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"We’ve all been there, but it’s a lot easier to acknowledge the problem than it is to prevent it from happening. Why? Because a lot of technologies are actually designed to make us miserable.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"That’s right. Good design can be terrible for us.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-3"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"If you’ve ever worked in advertising or marketing, you’ll be familiar with terms like “bounce rate” and “time on site”: in other words, “How long can we keep people interacting with our app?”","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"You’ll see this everywhere, from video games to shopping malls. A series of pleasing “micro-interactions” (notifications, animations, etc) cause our brains to release little bursts of a chemical called dopamine, which, contrary to what you might think, has very little to with feeling satisfied—in fact, it has quite the opposite effect.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"Dopamine: The Hungry Ghost","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-3"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"In Buddhism, the “hungry ghost” is a spirit driven by intense cravings that grow worse the more it seeks them out. This is a perfect analogy for ","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{"uri":"https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/brain-wise/201209/why-were-all-addicted-texts-twitter-and-google"},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"dopamine, which rewards us for seeking pleasures","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"hyperlink"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":", not attaining them.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"When we get stuck in a technology loop, each interaction increases our desire to seek out more stimulation, while simultaneously decreasing the satisfaction we receive and depleting the energy we need to resist.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"How to escape the loop","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-3"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"Everyone knows it’s a terrible idea to go to a casino without setting limits beforehand, but this concept can be incredibly helpful in preventing you from getting sucked into technology, as well.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"Here are a few tips:","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"Exit Strategy","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":" : Set a clear sign for when you’re going to stop (i.e. I’m getting off YouTube as soon as I’m done watching this video).","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"No Excuses","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":" : Don’t let yourself say “just one more”. We both know it’s never just one more.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"Quit Fast","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":" : Close the app, window, etc, the second you’re finished, or you’ll just get sucked in again.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"Prepare to Disengage","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":" : If you’re in the middle of a long experience (like a TV episode), start disengaging five minutes before it ends. Even looking away from the screen or thinking about what you’ll do afterwards can help prepare you to break away. Otherwise, you can get broad-sided by the real world, and it becomes much easier just to hit “Next Episode.”","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"}],"nodeType":"document"}},"__typename":"ContentfulArticle","id":"0fda9e96-5e82-5b12-95b1-d116c678d651","slug":"how-escape-technology-loop","title":"How to Escape a Technology Loop (aka Survive the 21st Century)","updatedAt":"2019-03-16T19:45:10.889Z","updatedAtString":"Mar 16, 2019 at 7:45pm","summary":{"text":"It’s 11:45, and you need a good night’s sleep badly, but your brain’s not cooperating. So you think… OK, I’ll just respond to a couple emails."},"fullPublishDate":"February 2, 2019","publishDate":"2019-02-12T08:00","author":{"name":"Andrew Folts","avatar":{"title":"Andrew Folts profile photo","alt":"","fluid":{"base64":"data:image/jpeg;base64,","aspectRatio":1,"src":"//images.ctfassets.net/jbawaa5001ko/2zp1feJo07IiG6YwZXudNr/ecc0f0eaf4e5952ddef7f0a3bb706569/smiling-lumberjack-1.jpg?w=750&q=50","srcSet":"//images.ctfassets.net/jbawaa5001ko/2zp1feJo07IiG6YwZXudNr/ecc0f0eaf4e5952ddef7f0a3bb706569/smiling-lumberjack-1.jpg?w=188&h=188&q=50 188w,\n//images.ctfassets.net/jbawaa5001ko/2zp1feJo07IiG6YwZXudNr/ecc0f0eaf4e5952ddef7f0a3bb706569/smiling-lumberjack-1.jpg?w=375&h=375&q=50 375w,\n//images.ctfassets.net/jbawaa5001ko/2zp1feJo07IiG6YwZXudNr/ecc0f0eaf4e5952ddef7f0a3bb706569/smiling-lumberjack-1.jpg?w=628&h=628&q=50 628w","sizes":"(max-width: 750px) 100vw, 750px"}}},"relatedArticles":null}},"pageContext":{"slug":"how-escape-technology-loop"}}